### useContext

`useContext` lets you subscribe to React context without nesting. It reads the current value of a context object created by `createContext`.

---

### Creating Context

```jsx
import { createContext } from 'react';

const ThemeContext = createContext('light');
```

### Providing Context

```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <ThemeContext.Provider value="dark">
      <Toolbar />
    </ThemeContext.Provider>
  );
}
```

### Consuming Context

```jsx
import { useContext } from 'react';

function Button() {
  const theme = useContext(ThemeContext);
  return <button className={`btn-${theme}`}>Click</button>;
}
```

### Multiple Contexts

```jsx
const UserContext = createContext(null);
const ThemeContext = createContext('light');

function Profile() {
  const user = useContext(UserContext);
  const theme = useContext(ThemeContext);
  return <div className={theme}>{user.name}</div>;
}
```

| Aspect | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| Purpose | Share data without prop drilling |
| Scope | All children within Provider |
| Re-render | All consumers re-render when value changes |
| Default value | Used when no Provider exists above |

> **Key Point:** Context is not a state management tool. Use it for global data like themes, locales, and auth. Overusing context can hurt performance since all consumers re-render on value change.

codeExample:
import { createContext, useContext, useState } from 'react';

const AuthContext = createContext(null);

function AuthProvider({ children }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);
  return (
    <AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, setUser }}>
      {children}
    </AuthContext.Provider>
  );
}

function useAuth() {
  return useContext(AuthContext);
}
